Food Security in Vietnam (2012–2021): A Geospatial Primer¶

Exploratory Spatial Data Analysis (ESDA) of Land Use and Demographic Variables¶

(Part of a broader study on Vietnam’s development and food security)

This project applies Exploratory Spatial Data Analysis (ESDA) to explore spatial patterns and dependencies in Vietnam's land use, demographic, and socioeconomic data from 2012 to 2021. Using spatial autocorrelation techniques like Moran’s I and Local Indicators of Spatial Association (LISA), the analysis identifies spatial clusters, outliers, and correlations between land use types (agriculture, forestry, homestead) and key demographic factors (population, income). The findings are visualized using choropleth maps to highlight geographic trends and insights related to food security.

key Components¶

  • Data Preparation
    Cleaned and preprocessed spatial data from multiple sources to ensure consistency and readiness for analysis.

  • Spatial Data Analysis
    Conducted global and local spatial autocorrelation to uncover spatial dependencies in land use and demographic variables using GeoPandas and PySAL.

  • Statistical Methods
    Applied Moran’s I and Local Indicators of Spatial Association (LISA) to detect clustering, dispersion, and outliers.

  • Geospatial Visualization
    Created choropleth maps and custom visualizations using Matplotlib and Folium to illustrate spatial trends and regional patterns clearly.

  • Interpretation of Spatial Patterns
    Identified and interpreted spatial clusters, geographic outliers, and relationships between land use types and demographic indicators.

Technologies Used:¶

  • Python, GeoPandas, PySAL, Matplotlib, Folium, Pandas

🗂️ Dataset Overview¶

All area units are in thousands of hectares (1 ha = 10,000 m²)
Income values are in thousand VND, adjusted for inflation to 2020 using VHLSS5

Column Description
Province Province name
AdminUnit Administrative unit name
TotalArea* Total land area of the unit
Agri* Agricultural land
Fores* Forestry land
Spec* Special-use land
Hmstd* Homestead/residential land
incm* Income (in thousand VND), adjusted to 2020
TotAvgPop_* Total average population (2012, 2016, 2020)
UrbanPop_* Urban population (2012, 2016, 2020)
RuralPop_* Rural population (2012, 2016, 2020)
Entpr_* Number of enterprises (by year)
Emply_* Enterprise employment (by year)

Groupings of Admin Units by Vietnam Yearbook

🗺️ Get Ready for Plotting

A reusable function is created to generate choropleth maps for land use over time. This supports consistent visualization of temporal change across different dimensions (e.g., total area, agriculture, forestry).

In [ ]:
from mpl_toolkits.axes_grid1 import make_axes_locatable
from matplotlib.colorbar import ColorbarBase
from matplotlib.colors import Normalize
from matplotlib.cm import ScalarMappable
In [ ]:
# plot map and color according to column in kml 
def plot1by3(col_set = ['TotalArea21','TotalArea16','TotalArea12']
            , colorscheme = 'YlOrBr'):
    
    """
    Creates a set of three choropleth maps displaying land area data (for the years 2012, 2016, 2021).
    Each map is colored according to the respective column in col_set.
    
    Parameters:
    col_set : list
        List of column names to plot (e.g., land area for different years).
    colorscheme : str
        Color map scheme to use for visualization.
    """

    # figure and axes
    fig, (ax0,ax1,ax2) = plt.subplots(1,3,figsize=(9, 6))

    # Set the background color
    fig.set_facecolor('gainsboro')
    
    ax_set = [ax0, ax1, ax2]     

    # Find the overall minimum and maximum values for color normalization
    overall_min = min(kmlfile[col].min() for col in col_set)
    overall_max = max(kmlfile[col].max() for col in col_set)

    # Loop through each axis and target column to create individual maps
    for ax,tgtcol in zip(ax_set, col_set):        

        # Plot df colors based on 'TotalArea'
        sm = kmlfile.plot(ax=ax
                , column=tgtcol
                , cmap=colorscheme
                , edgecolor='black'
                , legend=False)

        # Sort by 'TotalArea'
        kmlfile_sorted = kmlfile.sort_values(by=tgtcol)

        # Extract names of the two largest and two smallest provinces
        largest_provinces = kmlfile_sorted['Name'].tail(2).tolist()
        smallest_provinces = kmlfile_sorted['Name'].head(2).tolist()

        # Add plotting customizations
        titlestring = tgtcol + ' Use\nLargest 2:' \
                + largest_provinces[0] + ', ' + largest_provinces[1] + '\n'\
                + ' Smallest 2:' + smallest_provinces[0] + ', ' + smallest_provinces[1]
        ax.set_title(titlestring, fontsize=10)        
        ax.set_xticks([])
        ax.set_yticks([])
        ax.set_facecolor('#81a0af')
        ax.set_xlim((101.5,110))
        ax.set_ylim((8.2,23.5)) 

    # Add colorbar with shrink factor using ScalarMappable
    divider = make_axes_locatable(ax0)
    cax = divider.append_axes("left", size="5%",pad=0.1) 
    sm = ScalarMappable(cmap=colorscheme
                            , norm=Normalize(vmin=overall_min
                                            , vmax=overall_max))
    
    sm._A = []  # fake up the array of the scalar mappable
    cbar = fig.colorbar(sm, cax=cax)
    cbar.ax.yaxis.set_ticks_position('left')

    # prevent overlap
    fig.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

📈 Percentage Change in Area (2012–2021)¶

Objective: Show percentage change in total land area by administrative unit between 2012 and 2021. This helps identify regions with significant changes (e.g., due to redistricting or boundary adjustments).

  • Labels top 2 and bottom 2 provinces by area change.
  • Color scale emphasizes magnitude of percentage shifts.
In [ ]:
def areaPlot(tgtcol = 'TotalPctChg', colorscheme = 'YlOrBr'):

    """
    Creates a choropleth map displaying the percentage change in total area (2012 vs. 2021) across provinces.
    The color intensity reflects the magnitude of the change, with labels for the largest and smallest changes.
    
    Parameters:
    tgtcol : str
        The column name representing the percentage change (e.g., 'TotalPctChg').
    colorscheme : str
        Color map scheme to use for visualization.
    """

    # Create figure and axis
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(6, 7))

    # Set the background color 
    fig.set_facecolor('gainsboro')
    
    kmlfile.plot(ax=ax
                 , column=tgtcol
                 , cmap=colorscheme
                 , edgecolor='black'
                 , legend=False)

    # Sort by 'TotalArea'
    kmlfile_sorted = kmlfile.sort_values(by=tgtcol)

    # Extract names of the two largest and two smallest provinces
    largest_provinces = kmlfile_sorted['Name'].tail(2).tolist()
    smallest_provinces = kmlfile_sorted['Name'].head(2).tolist()


    # Add labels for the two largest and two smallest provinces
    for index, row in kmlfile.iterrows():
        if row['Name'] in largest_provinces + smallest_provinces:
            ax.text(row.geometry.centroid.x-1.8 #offset
                    , row.geometry.centroid.y
                    , row['Name']
                    , fontsize=10
                    , color='brown'
                    , ha='center'
                    , va='center')

    # Add plotting customizations
    titlestring = 'Vietnam Admin Districts % area change 2012 vs 2021\nLargest 2: ' \
        + largest_provinces[0] + ', ' + largest_provinces[1] + '\n'\
                + ' Smallest 2: ' + smallest_provinces[0] + ', ' + smallest_provinces[1]
    ax.set_title(titlestring, fontsize=12, loc='left')
    ax.set_xlabel('Latitude', fontsize=10)
    ax.set_ylabel('Longitude', fontsize=10)
    ax.set_facecolor('#81a0af')
    ax.set_xlim((101.5,110))
    ax.set_ylim((8.2,23.5))

    # Add colorbar with shrink factor using ScalarMappable
    divider = make_axes_locatable(ax)
    cax = divider.append_axes("right", size="5%", pad=0.1)
    sm = ScalarMappable(cmap=colorscheme
                        , norm=Normalize(vmin=kmlfile[tgtcol].min()
                                         , vmax=kmlfile[tgtcol].max()))

    sm._A = []  # fake up the array of the scalar mappable
    cbar = fig.colorbar(sm, cax=cax, label='Pct % change')  

    # Show the plot
    plt.show()

areaPlot()

Percentage change in AU land area from 2012 vs 2021

  • Top 2(smallest) AU change: Thua Thien Hue, Quang Binh

🧭 Land Use Shifts Across Time (2012–2021)¶

Before applying spatial autocorrelation techniques like Moran’s I and LISA, this section builds an intuitive baseline of where and how land use is shifting across Vietnam. Each land type is visualized through a set of temporal choropleths (2012, 2016, 2021), highlighting both national trends and local variations.

Internal reallocations on agricultural, forestry, homestead, and special-use land across administrative units may reflect economic development, urban pressure, or environmental stressors like saltwater intrusion.

These choropleths help surface early signals — spatial clustering, regional contrasts — that later analysis will quantify more formally.

🧭 Spatial Autocorrelation of Agricultural Land Use (2021)¶

After building a visual understanding of land use changes, this section takes things a step further by asking: Are these changes spatially connected? Using spatial autocorrelation techniques like Moran’s I and LISA, we explore whether provinces with similar agricultural land use tend to cluster — or stand apart.

We’ll begin with a global perspective to spot broad clustering patterns, then zoom into local regions to identify hotspots, coldspots, and outliers. Finally, we bring in other layers — income, population, enterprise, employment — to see how agricultural land use fits into the wider socioeconomic picture.

📈 Global Moran’s I¶

Objective: Measure overall spatial clustering in agricultural land use.

Global Moran’s I tells us whether agricultural land use is clustered in certain areas or spread out across the country. Essentially, it gives us a sense of how deeply entrenched agriculture is within the country’s landscape — if regions with similar agricultural land use are grouped together, we can infer that agriculture is more concentrated, rather than dispersed across urbanized or industrialized regions.

In [163]:
# Calculate spatial weights matrix
wmatrix = Queen.from_dataframe(kmlfile, geom_col='geometry', ids='Name')

# Calculate Moran's I statistic
moran = Moran(kmlfile.Agri21, wmatrix)

# Plot Moran's Scatterplot
fig, ax = moran_scatterplot(moran, aspect_equal=True)
fig.set_facecolor('gainsboro')
ax.set_facecolor('oldlace')

points = ax.collections[0]  
points.set_color('lightseagreen')

plt.ylabel('Spatial Lag of Agri21')
plt.xlabel('Agri21')

ax.annotate(f"Moran's I: {moran.I:.4f}; P-value: {moran.p_sim:.4f}\n" \
            + "neighbors weak spatial homogeneity;\nstatistically significant < 0.05"
            , xy=(0.7, -0.45)
            , ha='left', va='top', fontsize=10
            , bbox=dict(boxstyle='round', facecolor='wheat', alpha=0.5))

plt.show()

# Print Moran's I statistic and p-value
print(f"Moran's I: {moran.I}")
print(f"P-value: {moran.p_sim}")

Moran's I: 0.3086386678889503
P-value: 0.002
  • Global Moran's I at 0.3086, indicates moderate positive spatial autocorrelation — nearby AUs tend to have similar levels of agricultural land use.
  • Queen contiguity matrix used accounts for all neighboring directions

from splot.esda import lisa_cluster
In [170]:
def plot_lisa_cluster(moran_loc = None, kmlfile = None, 
                      p=0.05, fsize = (5,7),
                      title = 'Default title'):
    
    if (moran_loc == None):
        return
    if((kmlfile is None) or kmlfile.empty):
        return
    
    fig, ax = lisa_cluster(moran_loc, kmlfile, p=0.05, figsize = fsize)
    ax.set_title(title)

    # drop offshore island
    plt.xlim((101.5, 110))
    plt.ylim((8.2, 23.5))

    fig.set_facecolor('oldlace') 
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
    return

In [145]:
def plot_local_autocorr(moran_loc=None, kmlfile=None, title='Agri21', fsize=(10,4),
                        ax0_xlab = 'agriuse21', ax0_ylab = 'spatial lag',
                        ax1_title = 'LISA cluster', ax2_title='agriuse21'):
    
    if (moran_loc == None):
        return
    if((kmlfile is None) or kmlfile.empty):
        return
    
    fig,axs=plot_local_autocorrelation(moran_loc, kmlfile, title, figsize=fsize)
    
    axs[0].set_xlabel(ax0_xlab)
    axs[0].set_ylabel(ax0_ylab)
    axs[0].set_facecolor('oldlace')

    axs[1].set_title(ax1_title)
    axs[2].set_title(ax2_title)

    axs[1].set_facecolor('#81a0af')
    axs[1].set_xlim((101.5,110))
    axs[1].set_ylim((8.2,23.5))

    axs[2].set_facecolor('#81a0af')
    axs[2].set_xlim((101.5,110))
    axs[2].set_ylim((8.2,23.5))


    fig.set_facecolor('oldlace') 
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
    
    return

Bivariate Moran's I(agriculture land use vs population) and LISA

  • [red Hot spots] High agriculture land area, high population

    • occured in the south
    • corresponds to the known rice bowl mekong delta

  • [orange] High agriculture land area, low population

    • northern tip of country
    • surrounded by a low agriculture land use and low population band
    • basis to investigate since northern areas are mountainous and disadvantageous to agriculture
    • potentially the One Commune, One Product(OCOP) has yield results in Ha Giang agriculture sector goes far with OCOP products

  • [light blue] Low agriculture land area, high population

    • Seen at fringes of Hanoi in the Red River Delta
    • Supports the idea of urban expansion beyond the capital

  • [dark blue] Low agriculture land area, low population

    • Mostly in northern provinces where forestry dominates
    • Matches expectations for sparsely populated, mountainous zones

OTHER INFO¶

Temporal change in farm population¶

Vietnam underwent farm consolidation for resource optimization

Land allocation(%) to farm¶

From land allocated(pie chart) by province(bars) to number of farms(stacked bars)
reduced number of farms reflects consolidation though allocated agriculture land increased

Cultivation farms by Province¶

Cultivation concentrated in southern provinces

land allocation to cultivation output¶

translating land area to crop types and output

change in livestock farm count¶

farms concentrated around most populous AUs, indicative of higher income(corroborated by income plot) and accessibility to animal protein

Total Household income by AU¶

High income AUs concentrated around capital city, Ha Noi and Ho Chih Minh City. Income is likely derived from employment and high number of enterprises(corroborated by employment and enterprise count plots). Total monthly household income = Employment salary + Self-employment(AFF + Non-AFF) + Others

AFF: Agriculture, Forestry, Fishery

Household income spread by AU and Province¶

Spread of total household income components by province¶

poverty line indicative of food security amongst households

Temporal change in Total Income¶

changes from 2010(green, baseline) to 2016 and 2020. coloration in choropleth indicates rapid rise from 2010 to 2016 and slowdown between 2016 to 2020. The Central highlands appear to be particularly affected by the slowdown

Temporal change in AFF Income
2010(red, baseline) to 2016 and 2020. AFF income is on the decline, indicating Viet Nam's departure from AFF income.
